For {= specialty_contributor =}+ Detroit/Michigan-area specialty design/build contributors, find a public credit under each of the {= credit_source_role =} source roles listed below; for each contributor-role pair, identify {= public_credit =}+ distinct credit context and supply a source (i.e. {= url =}+ URL).

The source roles of interest, which we refer to as `credit_source_role`, are:
- `regional_media_award_credit`: a public credit recognized through regional design publishing, award, editorial, buyer-guide, sourcebook, or comparable publication treatment where the relevant section names the contributor in a specialty credit, award, category, room, project, or comparable public role.
- `direct_project_counterparty_credit`: a public credit recognized through page-visible direct project/work context from the contributor or a project counterparty, an actual individual showroom/display/installation credit, or a clearly project-specific profile surface whose primary subject is completed work and the cited contributor's role, rather than a regional-media, award, sourcebook, directory, resource-center, standalone showroom/vendor profile, display-index, product-line, or broad publication page.

`specialty_contributor` ought to be a real firm, studio, trade, fabricator, supplier, showroom, or commercial contributor in the Detroit/Michigan design/build ecosystem, such as stair/railing, architectural metal/glass, cabinetry, millwork, flooring, tile/stone, lighting, landscape, pool/hardscape, home technology, decorative finishes, fireplace, furnishings, custom fabrication, or a comparable specialty contributor. Primary architects, general builders, interior designers, design studios, generic retailers, consumer product brands, and broad resource directories are out of scope unless the named entity is page-visibly credited as the specialty actor itself, such as the trade, supplier, fabricator, showroom, installer, maker, artisan, or discrete specialty-service contributor. A specialty-named award category, room label, buyer-guide line, or team credit does not by itself convert a primary designer, architect, builder, developer, or broad design-build entrant into a specialty contributor. Landscape, pool, or design-build firms count only when the page-visible credit is for a landscape, hardscape, pool, lighting, masonry, outdoor-living, or comparable specialty scope rather than overall design/build authorship. The cited sources should be fully public, accessible, and usable as normal pages; search results, tag/category/archive pages, thin profiles/listings, standalone showroom/display, directory, vendor-profile, or product-line pages that only list suite, brand, category, service, availability, or contact details, shared resource-center pages that only list materials or services, copied image pins, login/paywall shells, and generic homepages or service pages without the cited credit are not qualifying.

Requirements:
- The page must clearly identify the named `specialty_contributor`.
- The page should tie the contributor or credit context to the Detroit/Michigan design ecosystem through regional publication framing, contributor location, project/partner location, showroom/display context, regional sourcebook context, or comparable page-visible regional context.
- The page should make its `credit_source_role` visible: for `regional_media_award_credit`, publication, award, editorial, buyer-guide, sourcebook, or media framing in the contributor's own relevant section; for `direct_project_counterparty_credit`, contributor-owned, counterparty-owned, direct project, gallery, case-study, partner, client/designer/builder, project-specific work framing, or an individual showroom/display surface that itself shows an actual project, installation, completed work, counterparty relationship, showroom event, or individual display/product credit, rather than media, award, buyer-guide, sourcebook, directory, resource-center, standalone showroom/vendor profile, display-index, product-line, or broad publication framing.
- The page must tie the contributor to a tangible public credit: a project, award entry, room or space, component, installed product, service scope, individual showroom/display credit, credited partner relationship, or comparable design/build contribution. Broad award, best-of, buyer-guide, and sourcebook pages need the contributor's own section to carry the credit; shared resource-center and material/service directory listings are not enough to establish a direct public credit by naming a firm and category alone. For `direct_project_counterparty_credit`, a standalone showroom, directory, vendor, display, or product-line profile does not establish a tangible direct credit by naming a suite, brands, product categories, services, availability, or contact details without page-visible project, installation, completed-work, counterparty, showroom-event, or individual display/product credit.
- The page should expose at least one archive-useful public context detail tied to the same contributor credit, such as publication or award year/date, issue, award category/place, article/project title, room or component label, partner/designer/builder name, public location scope, individual display/product/showroom-event label, or work-scope description.
